## Piano domain conventions

### Key mapping
- QWERTY row maps to white keys starting C4
- Map: A=C4, S=D4, D=E4, F=F4, G=G4, H=A4, 
  J=B4, K=C5
- Black keys on W E T Y U row
- Key names always use scientific notation: 
  "C4" not "middle C"
- Key map lives in src/audio/keyMap.ts — 
  single source of truth

### Audio
- Tone.js must not initialise until first 
  user gesture — wrap in Tone.start()
- Use Tone.Sampler not oscillators — 
  samples sound like a real piano
- Sampler must handle note release — 
  keydown triggers attack, keyup triggers release
- No audio state in React state — 
  audio lives in a ref or module singleton

### Song follow-along
- Songs are MIDI files in public/songs/
- Parse with @tonejs/midi on load
- Highlight = add CSS class to key component, 
  never manipulate DOM directly
- "Wait for correct key" mode must 
  pause Transport until right key pressed
- Song metadata (title, difficulty, tempo) 
  lives in src/songs/index.ts

### UI behaviour
- Pressed keys show visual depression 
  (transform + shadow via Framer Motion)
- Active highlights use a distinct colour 
  from pressed colour — never same shade
- On-screen keys must be clickable/tappable 
  as well as keyboard-driven
- Mobile: show on-screen keyboard 
  if no physical keyboard detected

## Agent behaviour
- Spawn subagents for independent workstreams 
  to keep each context window focused
- These are naturally parallel in this project:
  - Audio engine (Tone.js setup, sampler, 
    key triggers)
  - Piano UI components (keyboard layout, 
    key press animations)
  - Song system (MIDI parser, song metadata, 
    player logic)
  - Hooks and state (useKeyboard, useSong, 
    useAudio)
- Do not put audio logic in React components 
  — keep concerns separated so subagents 
  can work independently without conflicts
- Each subagent should own one folder in src/